\begin_layout Section
Intellectual Property
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intellectual property law is designed to protect creators' rights to their
 works, balancing the interests of authors, intermediaries, and the public.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Origins and Historical Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Intellectual property law has evolved significantly over time, tracing back
 to the Renaissance when the first copyright laws emerged to protect authors
 and inventors.
 The development of IP law reflects the changing societal views on creativity,
 innovation, and the dissemination of knowledge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Theoretical foundations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The core of IP law lies in recognizing and safeguarding the intellectual
 and creative labor of individuals, ensuring they can control and benefit
 from their creations.
 This legal framework seeks to stimulate crativity and innovation, while
 ensuring that the public can access and build upon existing works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Substantive Law
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Act of March 11, 1957 marked a shift towards a more industrial viewpoint
 of intellectual property, emphasizing the need for robust legal protection
 of creations without fundamentally altering the nature of copyright law.
 Its goals were to enhance legal protection, facilitate the dissemination
 of works, and streamline the consultation process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Acr of July 3, 1985 introduced the codification of IP laws, organizing
 and clarifying the rules to make them more accessible and systematic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Protected Works
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be protected under IP law, according to Article L.
 111-1 of the French IP Code, works must be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Original
\series default
: the work has the personal stamp of its creator, reflecting their choices
 and personality.
 This principle applies across different forms of IP, including copyright
 and patent law, where the focus is on the uniqueness of the expression
 or invention rather than the novelty or utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Materialized
\series default
: it needs to be physically done.
 Ideas are not protected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Originality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Originality is not explicitly defined but is understood as the unique expression
 of the creator's personality in the work.
 Article L.
 112-1 emphasizes that protection covers all intellectual works, regardless
 of their form, merit, or purpose, as long as they reflect the author's
 personal contribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This concept is 
\series bold
flexible
\series default
, allowing for a broad interpretation of what contributes a protectable
 work.
 This flexibility extends to adaptations of pre-existing works, which can
 be considered original if they sufficiently reflect the author's personal
 creativity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, Marcel Duchamp's works, such as his readymades, challenge tradition
al notions of originality and creativity.
 By selecting everyday objects and presenting them as art, Duchamp's contributio
ns lie in the idea and conceptual shift rather than in traditional artistic
 craftmanship.
 This raises interesting questions about where the line is drawn between
 idea and expression in art, reflecting the broader challenges with IP law
 of defining and protecting original works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Protection Without Formalities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
IP law grants authors exclusive rights to their creations without the need
 for formal registration processes.
 This principle, anchored in Article L.
 111-1 of the French IP Code, ensures that creators enjoy rights from the
 moment of creation, diverging from traditional copyright laws requirinig
 formal registration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Safeguards and systems for protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
EU Directive 2001
\series default
: integrated into French law, this directive enhances protections for works
 shared on the Internet, addressing modern challenges in IP law.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Deposit Systems
\series default
: while formal registration is not required for protection, deposit systems
 such as legal deposits, public registers for films, audiovisual works,
 and national registers for designs serve as additional safeguards.
 For example, publishers submitting copies of books to a national library
 as part of the legal system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Private Deposit Systems
\series default
: tools like the Soleau envelope or public notary deposits offer creators
 a means to document the creation date and details of their work, providing
 evidence that can be useful in disputes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Indifference to the Genre, Form of Expression, Merit and Purpose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Article L.
 112-1 emphasizes that copyright protection extends to all intellectual
 works, regardless of their genre, form of expression, merit, or purpose.
 This inclusive approach ensures broad protection for creators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
genre
\series default
 is the category of artistic composition to which the work in question belongs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
form of expression
\series default
 is the creative process or technique used within this genre.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The boundary between technical know-how and creative expression poses challenges
 to IP law, illustrated by varying court decisions on whether a perfume's
 scent can be copyrighted.
 The Paris Court of Appeal and the Cour de Cassation have diverged in their
 rulings, highlighting the complexities of defining what constitutes a protectab
le work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Merit and public morals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Merit
\series default
: IP protection is not contingent on a work's aesthetic value.
 Video games, for instance, have been recognized for legal protection as
 original intellectual creations regardless of artistic merit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Public morals
\series default
: protection extends to works without regard to their conformity to public
 morals.
 However, the law remains sensitive to the public interest and moral standards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Manual copies
\series default
: the Cour de Cassation has ruled that manual reproductions of artworks
 can qualify as derivative works eligible for copyright protection, emphasizing
 the personal touch involved in such reproductions.
 For instance, copies made in a museum are considered a lawful activity
 as long as the work is not sold as an original work of art and it is compulsory
 to use a canvas of a special size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Purpose and the Unity of Art principle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distinction between pure art is often blurred, leading to debates over
 what qualifies for protection.
 The principle of the 
\series bold
Unity of Art
\series default
 advocates for a broad interpretation, extending copyright proection to
 a wide range of creations, from functional objects like bottle openers
 to traditional art forms like statues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Application of the Protection Criterion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Article L.
 112-2 of the French IP Code provides an indicative list of protected works,
 but protection is not limited to this list.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Staging of performing arts events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
General rule
\series default
: the staging of performing arts events is typically not considered a work
 eligible for copyright protection because such events are often viewed
 as performances rather than creative works in themselves.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Exception
\series default
: a director who significantly modifies or adds original elements to hiw
 own work can transform a performance into a protectable work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Collections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
General rule
\series default
: collections or series or works that are not inter-related are generally
 not considered individual works of copyright.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
The Schlumpf affair
\series default
: this case highlighted the complexity of determining copright eligibility
 for collections.
 This case involved a controversy over the collection of vintage automobiles
 by Fritz Schlumpf, one of the most prominent car collections in the world.
 The legal disputes primarily focused on issues of ownership, classification
 of the collection as cultural heritage, and the rights associated with
 the collection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Contrasting case
\series default
: the Henri Langlois cinema museum case offered an opposite solution, recognizin
g certain collections as protectable under copyright law.
 Unlike the Schlumpf Affair, which centered around ownership and heritage
 classification, issues around the cinema museum could touch upon copyright
 considerations, especially concerning the protection of film archives,
 promotional materials, and other items that involve creative expression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Language and computer science
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Language
\series default
: the borrowing of extensive portions from scholarly works on specific languages
, like the example involving Cajun and Hermann languages, demonstrates the
 challenges in protecting language-based works when they lack original expressio
n.
 However, inventions like the creative narrative in 
\emph on
Clockwork Orange
\emph default
, can qualify for protection if they embody original creative expression.
 This is a novel by Anthony Burgess, adapted into a film by Stanley Kubrick.
 The work is known for its inventive language (Nadsat) and its exploration
 of themes like free will, violence, and societal control.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Computer science
\series default
: generally, the field is seen as technical and not eligible for copyright.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Exceptional consideration of work's purpose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
General rule
\series default
: documents intended for widespread public circulation are usually not protected
 to ensure access to information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Annotations
\series default
: in contrast, original annotations or commentary accompanying such documents
 can be protected, highlighting the importance of creative expression over
 the informational content.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Speeches
\series default
: both general speeches and those in legal settings may receive protection,
 albeit with certain limitations to balance freedom of expression and informatio
n dissemination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Visual arts: composition and expression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Handmade copies
\series default
: reproductions of artworks, if created by hand, can be considered derivative
 works eligible for proteciton, emphasizing the role of the artist's personal
 touch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Expression vs.
 Composition
\series default
: the law often distinguishes between the 
\emph on
expression
\emph default
 of ideas (protected) and the 
\emph on
composition
\emph default
 of ideas (not protected), underscoring the principle that copyright protects
 the form of expression rather than the idea itself.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For example, consider a recipe for a cake:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Composition: the list of ingredients for the cake and the basic steps represents
 the composition.
 This aspect is generally not copyrightable because it pertains to the idea
 or functional aspect of making a cake.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Expression: the way the recipe is written, including the narrative style,
 unique instructions, personal anecdotes, or creative presentation in a
 cookbook, constitutes the expression.
 This can be copyrighted because it reflects the author's original way of
 expressing the idea of making a cake.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Application of the Criterion of Originality: Special Cases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Photographic Works
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pre-1985 view: originality was often tied to the artistic merit of the photograp
h, leading to conflicts with the broader principles of copyright law, which
 seeks to protect the expression of ideas rather than their artistic value
 or merit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Post-1985 view (Lang Act): this legislation clarified that the sole criterion
 for the copyright protection of photographs ir originality, emphasizing
 the photographer's personal creative choices, such as angle, lighting,
 and composition, over the subject matter itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Controversy over artwork photos: new debates have arisen regarding the copyright
ability of photographs of artworks, especially when such photographs attempt
 to replicate the original works as faithfully as possible without adding
 any personal creative contribution.
 When they are original, they are considered derivative works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a photograph capturing a unique moment or perspective, such
 as a specific lighting effect or angle on a common subject, can demonstrate
 the photographer's personal stamp, making it eligible for copyright protection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Titles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Article L.
 112-4 IPC: titles can be protected under copyright, unfair competition,
 and trademark law, depending on their originality, distinctiveness, and
 potentional confusion with existing titles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Originality and distinctiveness: the protection of titles hinges on their
 ability to reflect the author's personal creativity.
 Given the brevity of titles, this often involves assessing their unconventional
 aspects or how they contribute to the work's identity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Translations: the originality of translations, including titles, is evaluated
 based on whether they offer a ltieral rendering of the original or incorporate
 creative choices that distinguish them as new, original works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a title like 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The Unbearable Lightness of Being
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\emph default
 reflects the author's personal creativity and is distinctive enough to
 be protected under copyright law.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Derivative Works, Collections and Databases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Degree of originality: the focus is on the originality manifested either
 in the selection and arrangement of the contents (for collections and databases
) or in the adaptations and transformations made to existing works (for
 derivative works).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Legal evolution: the law has evolved to recognize that the originality criterion
 can be met by the original selection or arrangement of materials within
 a collection or database, as seen in changes to Article L.
 112-3.
 Port-1998, for copyright to apply, the collection or database must exhibit
 originality in the choice or presentation of its contents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, an anthology of poems selected and arranged in a manner that
 reflects the compiler's unique vision or perspective on the theme, thereby
 qualifying as an original work due to the originality in selection and
 presentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Authorship and Ownership of the Rights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Authorship
\series default
 refers to the creation and original expression found in the work, attributing
 the work to the individual or group who conceived it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Ownership
\series default
 pertains to the bundle of rights associated with the work, including the
 right to reproduce, distribute, perform, display, or create derivative
 works.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While authorship is inalienable and permanently tied to the creator, ownership
 of rights can be transferred or licensed to others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ownership belongs to the author 
\emph on
Ab Initio
\emph default
, meaning that from the moment of creation, ownership of the rights to a
 work inherently belongs to the author.
 This principle affirms the personal connection between a creator and their
 creation, ensuring the creator's initial control over how the work is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Principles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to Article L.
 111-1, only natural persons can be recognized as authors, emphasizing the
 requirement for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

minimum of freedom of creation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that allows individuals to express their personality through their works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A contractual agreement cannot alter the status of an individual as the
 author of a work.
 This status is inherent and protected by law, regardless of any agreements
 concerning the transfer of ownership rights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Presumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Legal fact and simple presumption (Article L.
 113-1): the law provides for a simple presumption that the person under
 whose name the work is published is the author, barring evidence to the
 contrary.
 This presumption facilitates the enforcement of copyright and the attribution
 of authorship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Judicial presumption for legal entities: since 1993, a judicial presumption
 allows legal entities to act as the owners of copyright for works published
 under their name, particularly in cases of exploitation.
 This presumption addresses the practical aspects of copyright enforcement,
 especially concerning third-party infringers, but does not negate the principal
 that only natural persons can be authors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Special Cases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
IP law encounters unique challenges when addressing works that involve collabora
tion or non-traditional forms of creation and attribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Work designed by one artist and produced by another person
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the interwar period, Dunand, an artist, designed decorative items
 for large liners.
 While Dunand conceived and designed these items, they were physically produced
 by technicians who had no creative freedom in their execution.
 In this scenario, Dunand retains the copyright for his original designs,
 as the creative force behind the work.
 This emphasizes the distinction between the conception of a work and its
 material execution, with copyright protection extending to the creative
 idea and design rather than the manual labor of production.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Derivative works: the role of the engraver
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An engraver who transposes a drawing or a painting into an engraving does
 more than merely reproduce the original work; they interpret and recreate
 it, thus producing a derivative work.
 This process involves creativity and personal input that can qualify the
 resulting engraving as a new, copyrighted work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Material execution: the Renoir/Guino affair
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This case highliths the significance of material execution in determining
 copyright.
 When a work is conceived by one person but executed by another, legal and
 doctrinal debates arise regarding who holds the copyright.
 In the Renoir/Guino affair, sculptures conceived by Renoir and executed
 by Guino raised questions about the attribution of copyright, illustrating
 how collaborative works challenge traditional notions of authorsgip and
 ownership.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Anonymous works or works published under a pseudonym
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Author's choice and responsibility: authors may choose to publish works
 anonymously or under a pseudonym, which can complicate copyright attribution.
 If the author's identity is not disclosed, the responsibility lies with
 the author or their representatives to maintain secrecy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Calculation of rights: for anonymous or pseudonymous works, copyright duration
 is typically set at 70 years from the date of publication, unless the author's
 identity is revealed earlier.
 This ensures that the works remain protected while accounting for the uncertain
ty regarding the author's identity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Author's Status: Paid Employee, Civil Servant or Working To Order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The underlying principle in all these scenarios is that copyright rights
 inherently belong to the author from the moment of creation, with specific
 legal nuances based on the context.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Employment contract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
General rule (Article L.
 111-1)
\series default
: the mere existence of an employment contract does not automatically transfer
 copyright from the author to the mployer, ensuring that authors retain
 their rights unless explicitly transferred through an agreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Collective work exception
\series default
: the rights to works created as part of a collective effort may be presumed
 to belong to the employer, especially when the work's creation is within
 the scope of employment duties and intended as a collective project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a graphic designer employed by an advertising agency creates
 artwork for a campaign.
 While the agency may own the physical designs, copyright remains with the
 designer unless explicitly transferred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Commissioning contract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cour de Cassation ruling: echoing the principle, any transfer of copyright
 principles in the context of a commissioned work must be explicitly agreed
 upon in a contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ownership VS materialization: while the physical medium of a work can be
 owned by the commissioning party, the IP rights remain with the author
 unless specifically transferred.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, an author is commissioned to write a novel for a publishing
 house.
 The copyright belongs to the author, and specific rights to publish and
 distribute the book would need to be contractually transferred to the publisher.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Public officials or civil servants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pre-2006 position: traditionally, public officials were not entitled to
 copyright over works created as part of their official duties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2006 legal reform: introduced nuances to this rule, allowing for exceptions
 (though no exception is defined) where public officials could retain copyright
 on their works, with particular emphasis on situations where their professional
 duties do not inherently involve creating copyrightable works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a researcher employed by a government agency develops a new
 analytical method.
 The copyright rights associated to this method are public.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Collective works
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A collective work is characterized by contributions from multiple authors
 who work under the incitative and direction of a person or entity that
 publishes the work under its name.
 In such cases, copyright rights may belong to the publisher or commissioning
 entity, recognizing their role in organizing, financing, and managing the
 creation and publication of the work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even in this context, the individual authors' moral rights remain protected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a publisher commissions a series of essays from various authors
 and publishes them as a single volume under the publisher's name.
 The publisher may hold the copyright for the collection as a collective
 work, while individual authors retain rights to their respective essays.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Works Created by Several Authors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A work of joint authorship involves the creative contributions of several
 natural persons, classified not by the extent of each person's contribution
 but by the collective effort towards a common project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, an interview may typically credit the journalist as the author.
 However, if the interviewee significantly shapes the content or presentation,
 as in the case provided, they can also be considered a joint author.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The regime, according to Article L.
 113-3, states that rights to the work are shared among co-authors, requiring
 unanimity for decisions regarding exploitation and defense of the work.
 Each co-author retains moral rights over their contribution and the work
 as a whole.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Duration of legal protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general rule, according to Article L.
 123-2, states that the copyright term for works of joint authorship lasts
 until 70 years after the death of the last surviving co-author, ensuring
 extended protection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A special regime applies, considering specific roles (e.g., scriptwriter,
 director, composer) as co-authors, with the term determined by the death
 of the last co-author from a pre-established list.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Works under one's name
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Works created under the initiative and name of a publisher or legal entity,
 where individual contributions merge into the collective work, making it
 difficult to attribute distinct rights to any one author.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jurisprudence differentiates between contributions to a collective work
 and independent works, requiring explicit transfer of rights for elements
 not inherently part of the collective creation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Remuneration of the author
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Typically, authors contributing to a work of joint authorship are entitled
 to remuneration proportional to their contribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For certain types of works, like dictionaries and periodicals, flat-rate
 payments can be established, acknowledging the standardized nature of contribut
ions to these collective works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Authors' legal rights over their contributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contributors must be able to identify their contributions, which can be
 exploited separately, provided this does not affect the overall exploitation
 of the joint work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the collective work's purpose cannot be altered without consent, individua
l contributors retain moral rights over their contributions, ensuring respect
 for their personal connection to the work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Composite or derivative works
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Composite or derivative works represents a significant category within intellect
ual property law, involving the creation of new works that incorporate pre-exist
ing ones without the original author's collaboration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Composite work (article L.
 113-2)
\series default
: a new creation that includes a pre-existing work, either through transformatio
n (intellectual incorporation) or by including the material as is (material
 incorporation), without the participation of the original author.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Rights and Ownership (article L.
 113-4)
\series default
: while the composite work is the property of the author who produced it,
 this ownership respects the rights of the original author.
 The original author retains the exclusive and absolute right to authorize
 or forbid the use of their work within the new creation, typically receiving
 compensation for its use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
La cage aux folles
\emph default
 case: an Italian producer obtained the international film rights for this
 film, with the exception that the play could not be directly adapted into
 an English-language film produced in USA.
 When the play was later adapted into a Broadway musical, which was then
 adapted into a film, the Italian producer argued that this constituted
 a direct adaptation of the original play, violating the agreement.
 The Cour de Cassation ruled in favor of the Italian producer, highlighting
 the nuanced interpretation of adaptation rights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
La Tosca
\emph default
 case: the Italian publishers who held the rights to this opera, which was
 based on the play, sold the film adaptation rights without seeking permission
 from the original author's heirs for this new form of adaptation.
 The Court ruled that the permission granted by the original author was
 limited and did not extend to film adaptations, ilustrating that each new
 adaptation form might require explicit authorization from the copyright
 holder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While adaptations may take liberties with the original material, there is
 a legal and moral expectation that they respect the spirit and substance
 of the original work.
 However, case law has shown a liberal stance towards adaptations, as demonstrat
ed by the adaptations of 
\emph on
Fantômas
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Le Petit Prince
\emph default
, where significant changes were deemed to respect the original spirit,
 though not without controversy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Status of the author of the composite work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The individual who adapts a pre-existing work into a new form is considered
 the sole author of the composite work, with specific provisions for audiovisual
 productions recognizing the collective nature of such creations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The protection of the composite work follows common law provisions, lasting
 70 years after the death of the last surviving author.
 Notably, agreements can limit the period during which an adaptation is
 authorized, affecting the duration of the exploitation rights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Final considerations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Creative freedom VS rights of the original author: while there is considerable
 creative freedom in making adaptations, it's crucial to negotiate and respect
 the rights and expectations of the original author, including compensatory
 agreements and adherence to the original work's spirit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Legal agreements: explicit agreements detailing the scope of adaptation
 rights and any limitations on the exploitation of the composite work are
 essential to prevent legal disputes and ensure that all parties' rights
 are protected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Moral rights: the case law underscores the importance of balancing the adapter's
 creative expression with the need to respect the original work's integrity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Exclusive Right of the Author Over His or Her Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exclusive rights of authors over their works are an important issue
 of copyright law, granting creators control over how their works are used,
 distributed, and modified.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two aspects:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Unfinished works
\series default
: authors have exclusive rights over their unfinished works, protecting
 them from unauthorized use, publication, or distribution.
 This ensures that authors can control the completion and release of their
 works according to their vision and timing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Distinction between tangible and intangible ownership
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Article L.
 111-2 establishes that the ownership of a work is distinct from the ownership
 of the material object in which the work is materialized.
 For example, owning a painting physically does not grant the owner copyright
 over the artistic work itseld.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Article L.
 111-3 addresses situations where an author needs access to the original
 work, that is in the possession of another party for the purpose of exploiting
 the work.
 If the holder of the physical object refuses access and this refusal constitute
s manifest abuse, legal sanctions can be applied to ensure the author's
 rights are respected.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
For works that are published posthumously or long after their creation,
 there is an additional protection period.
 Works published for the first time after the end ot the copyright monopoly
 are granted an additional monopoly of 25 years.
 This extension aims to protect the interests of the authors or their heirs,
 encouraging the publication of previously unnplublished works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Moral Right
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moral rights represent the personal and perpetual connection between an
 author and their work, reflecting an aspect of the author's personality
 rather than their pecuniary interests.
 Unlike patrimonial rights, moral rights safeguard the personal and reputational
 interests of authors in their works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moral rights are not about ethical or moral behavior but concern the protection
 of the author's personal relationship with their work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These rights defend the non-financial interests of authors, ensuring respect
 for their creation and integrity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Characters Involved
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Article L.
 121-1 states that moral rights are inherently linked to the author as an
 individual, underscoring the work as an extension of the author's personality.
 These rights are perpetual, even passing to the heirs, and are inalienable,
 meaning they cannot be transferred or renounced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There is an exception for works of joint authorship, in which certain moral
 rights can be attributed to the publisher.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The principal characteristics of moral rights are that they are inalienable
 and perpetual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moral rights are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Paternal right
\series default
: authors have the right to be recognized as the creator of the work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Disclosure right
\series default
: authors have the right to decide when or if their work is published.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Legal proceedings and enforcement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Exercise of rights: authors are free to exercise their moral rights without
 limitation, including initiating legal actions to defend these rights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Abuse of rights: while authors have broad discretion in exercising their
 moral rights, heirs may face accusations of abusing these rights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Enforceability and devolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Perpetual right: the perpetual nature of moral rights means they persist
 indefinitely, not subbject to waiver or loss through non-use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Devolution system: Articles L.
 121-1 and 2 outline how moral rights may be managed after the author's
 death, including provisions for the court to make decisions in the interest
 of preserving the authpr's legacy in cases where there are no direct heirs
 of the heirs intentions are unclear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Attributes of Moral Rights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Right to disclose the work (Article L.
 121-2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This right allows the author exclusively to decide when, how, and if their
 work should be made public.
 It encompasses various forms of making the work available to the public,
 including publishing, public exhibition and theatrical performances.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decision to disclose a work directly affects its copyright status and,
 by extension, its property rights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The author's intention to disclose must be explicit.
 Depositing manuscripts in archives or entrusting paintings to a gallery
 without explicit intent for public exhibition does not consitute discloure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right of disclosure is absolute, but nuances exist, such as the possibility
 of new disclosures if the form of expression changes significantly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Right of disclosure and commissioning contract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
whistler jurisdprudence
\series default
 refers to the principle that ownership of a commissioned work transfers
 to the commissioner only upon the work's completion and delivery.
 If an author refuses to disclose a commissioned work, legal and monetary
 implications are considered, focusing on the duty to complete the commission
 and the potential for damages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Right to the respect of the name, paternity, and integrity of the work (Article
 L.
 121-1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Authors have the right to be recognized as the creators of their work and
 to protect the work from any alterations that could harm their reputation
 or the work's integrity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These moral rights can limit how a work is used or modified, regardless
 of who holds the economic rights, with certain allowances for criticism
 and adaptation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thile moral rights protect the work's integrity, they do not prevent legitimate
 criticism or commentary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Right of withdrawal or reconsideration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This right allows the author to retract their work from the public domain
 or modify it after publication, under the condition that any damage to
 the licensee or assignee is compensated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If an author decides to re-exploit the work, the original licensee or assignee
 may have a priority right to be the first to exploit the new version under
 the initially agreed conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Patrimonial Rights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Patrimonial rights allow authors to derive financial benefit from their
 works through the exclusive control over reproduction, distribution, and
 other forms of exploitation.
 These rights are fundamental to copyright law, enabling creators to authorize
 or prohibit the use of their works in various ways.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Principle of Exclusive Right
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The author possesses the exclusive right to exploit their work in any form
 and to gain financial rewards from such exploitation.
 This encompasses both the right to authorize specific uses of the work
 and the right to prohibit other from exploiting it without permission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While inherently individual, the management of these rights can be collectively
 organized, especially concerning rights that are difficult to enforce on
 an individual basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two main powers originally granted by the code, and a third added
 one:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Right of reproduction
\series default
: defined as the material fixation of the work allowing it to be communicated
 to the public indirectly.
 This includes digital reproduction on computer systems, temporary copies,
 and partial reproductions, subject to authorial consent unless exceptions
 apply (e.g., quotations or educational use).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Right of public performance
\series default
: involves the right to control the public presentation of the work, whether
 through physical performance, broadcasting, or digital streaming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Right of resale
\series default
: entitles the author to a percentage of the sale price each time the work
 is resold, providing ongoing benefits from the work's circulation in the
 art market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Right of Reproduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
EU definition
\series default
 encompasses the comprehensive right to authorize or prohibit any form of
 reproduction, highlighting the breadth of control authors have over their
 creations.
 The law also specifies certain situations where reproduction does not require
 the author's permission, such as for educational or research purposes,
 maintaining a balance between copyright protection and public interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Adaptation rights
\series default
: these rights are closely linked to moral rights, ensuring that adaptations
 respect the original work's integrity and that authors control how their
 work is transformed or adapted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Right of destination
\series default
: authors must authorize any change in the use of their work, such as converting
 a novel into a screenplay or changing the format from physical to digital,
 ensuring control over the work's exploitation across different mediums
 and contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Collective management (Article L.
 122-10)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The law mandates the automatic transfer of reprographic reproduction rights
 to a collective management organization, facilitating the efficient management
 and enforcement of these rights, particularly in contexts like photocopying,
 where individual enforcement is impractical.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Right of Public Performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This right encompasses any form of dissemination that makes the work accessible
 to people beyond a private circle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key aspects of this right are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Broad definition (Article L.
 122-2)
\series default
: this right covers the communication of the work by any means, including
 live performances, broadcasting, and digital streaming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Potential audience
\series default
: the definition of public performance includes situations where the audience
 is merely potential, expanding the scope of what constitutes a public communica
tion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
New public
\series default
: any act that targets a new audicence or public is considered a new act
 of public performance, necessitating authorization from the rights holder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Online availability
\series default
: making a work available online is deemed a public performance because
 it allows potential access by a broad audience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Exceptions to Exploitations Rights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the transposition of the EU Directive in 2006, the scope of exception
 to exploitation rights, including the right of public performance, has
 expanded, balancing copyright protection with fundamental freedom and fair
 use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conditions for exceptions are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No interference with normal exploitation: exception must not disrupt the
 typical market exploitation of the work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No prejudice to the author's interests: they should not unjustly harm the
 author's legitimate interests.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Published works: generally, the work must have been made publicly available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some specific exceptions are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Private copies
\series default
: this exception applies to copies made for personal, non-commercial use.
 This does not extend to software programs and databases, and only a single
 copy is permitted.
 Also, the original work from which the copy is made must be legally acquired,
 adhering to the principle 
\emph on

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fraus omnia corrumpit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\emph default
 (fraud corrupts everything).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Short quotations
\series default
: allowed when justifiable by critical, debate, educational, scientific,
 or intructional nature.
 The quotations must not infringe upon the moral rights of the author, and
 the length of the quotation must be considered in relation to the size
 of the original and derivative works and the purpose of its inclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Works that can be quoted include literary texts, articles, reports, and
 portions of musical compositions, provided the quotations are used within
 a context that justifies their inclusion, such as academic works, criticism,
 or news reporting.
 The work being quoted must be adequately attributed to its original author,
 respecting the right of paternity.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Resale Rights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Resale rights, historically unique to certain jurisdictions like France,
 have seen broader adoption internationally, including in the US, Germany,
 and other countries, due to efforts toward harmonization within the EU.
 However, the regulation of these rights has been critized for its negotiation
 and implementation inconsistencies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Resale rights
\series default
 entitle the original artist to a percentage of the sale price each time
 their work is resold on the art market.
 This applies particularly to graphic and visual arts, including original
 works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Roding Jurisprudence
\series default
 clarifies that original works eligible for resale rights include those
 made directly by the artist or limited copies produced under the artist's
 supervision.
 This ensures artists continue to benefit from the increasing value of their
 works over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Agreements to Exploit the Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exploitation of an author's work through various means, such as public
 performance, publication, or audiovisual production, requires explicit
 and personal consent from the author, typically mandated to be in writing
 to ensure clarity and enforceability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key requirements and principles are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Written consent (Article L.
 131-2)
\series default
: consent for agreements related to significant forms of exploitation must
 be documented in writing, detailing the rights being assigned and the scope
 of the agreement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Restrictive interpretation
\series default
: rights assigned through contracts are interpreted restrictively, with
 any ambiguities resolved in favor of the author.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Independence of rights (Articles L.
 111-3 and L.
 122-7 CPI)
\series default
: the transfer of IP rights is distinct from the transfer of the physical
 medium, and transferring one exploitation right does not imply the transfer
 of the others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Specification of terms
\series default
: contracts must specify the duation, scope, type of exploitation, and geographi
c location to be valid.
 Absence of a time period or failure to delineate the scope renders the
 contract void.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Audiovisual adaptation
\series default
: rights concerning audiovisual adaptations require a reparate agreement,
 emphasizing the specificity needed in cotnracts regarding different forms
 of exploitation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Future works (Article L.
 131-6)
\series default
: the law prohibits agreements that transfer rights to future works in a
 broad or unspecified manner, protecting authors from exploitative practices.
\end_layout

