\begin_layout Section
Industrial Property
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
What's A Patent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A patent is an immaterial title of private property granted by one or more
 states, providing a temporary monopoly on a novel and inventive invention.
 In exchange for this monopoly, the invention is published, making the details
 available to the public.
 The creation of a patent involves filing and examination processes, with
 a standard lifetime of 20 years.
 Patent law varies by country but operates within a broader intelelctual
 property (IP) toolbox that includes patents, utility models, design patents,
 trademarks, copyright, and protections for printed circuit borad topographies
 and databases, as well as animal and vegetal production processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Patent VS Trademark
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Patents grant a temporary monopoly on technical inventions that meet criteria
 of novelty, inventiveness, and industrial applicability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Trademarks protect distinctive names, logos, or symbols used to identify
 products or services, offering an unlimited renewable lifetime, country-depende
nt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Obtaining and exploiting a patent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The process includes filing an application, which is then examined for novelty,
 inventive step, and industrial applicability.
 Once granted, the patent holder has the exclusive right to exploit the
 invention, which includes manufacturing, selling, or licensing the patented
 product or process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Other kinds of industrial property
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Utility model: a simplified patent.
 This protects inventions without requiring strong inventive steps, with
 shorther protection term than patents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Design model: protects the aesthetic aspects or appearance of a product,
 not its technical features.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Printed circuit board topographies and databases: specific protections for
 the design of circuit boards and the organization of databases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Animal and vegetal production processes: special categories for agricultural
 innovations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Territorial validity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
France: governed by the Code de la Propriété Intellectuelle (CPI), covering
 various forms of IP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Europe: The European Patent Convention (EPC) and the Unitary Patent Court
 (UPC) system provide frameworks for European patents and the upcoming unitary
 patent system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
USA: patents are governed by Title 35 of the US Code, with criteria focusing
 on utility, novelty, and non-obviousness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
WTO: the Trade-Related Aspects of Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPS) agreement
s set minimum standards for IP protection, including patents, applicable
 to member states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Object of the Patent Application
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Patentability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Patentability criteria ensure that only inventions meeting specific standards
 can be protected by patentes.
 These criteria are designed to promote genuine innovation and contribute
 to technological advancement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To be patentable, the work must be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Technical invention
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Possess 
\series bold
industrial application
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Novel
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Involve an 
\series bold
inventive step
\series default
 (non-obviousness).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Invention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subject matter of the patent must be a technical innovation.
 This can be a product, process, or any new and useful improvement thereof,
 capable of industrial application.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a new type of battery with improved energy efficiency or a
 novel method for prifying water using less energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several kinds of inventions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
New solution to a known technical problem: innovations that provide new
 ways to address existing technical challenges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Selecting an optimal solution: choosing the most effective solution from
 a range of known options based on new criteria or considerations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Identifying a new technical effect: discovering previously unknown benefits
 or effects or a known method, device, or system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Formulating a new technical problem: recognizing and defining a previously
 unaddressed technical issue that requires a novel solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Industrial Application
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The invention must be useful; it has to have a practical application in
 any field of industry, including agriculture, fisheries, and services.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Certain fields might be excluded from patentability due to ethical reasons,
 lack of industrial applicability, or being mere abstract concepts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a machine that automates a specific manufacturing process is
 patentable due to its direct industrial application.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Invention + Industrial Application
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The combination of having a technical solution to a problem or identifying
 a new technical problem with the requirement for industrial applicability
 ensures that patents are granted to innovations that offer practical technical
 improvements and are capable of being used in industrial settings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Novelty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The invention must be new or novel, meaning it cannot be part of the state
 of the art.
 State of the art includes anything that has been publicly disclosed, published,
 or otherwise made available to the public anywhere in the world before
 the filing date.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, an electronic device featuring a never-before-seen combination
 of functionalities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Inventive Step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The invention must involve an inventive step, making it not obvious to a
 person skilled in the art.
 This criterion assesses whether the invention is a sufficient advance over
 what is already known.
 A person skilled in the art is a technician, in the technical field of
 the invention, that holds standard knowledge of the fields, and some knowledge
 in fields close to it, and with access to all documents that are available
 in the state of the art.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, a new method for conducting wireless communication that significant
ly reduces signal interference, which would not have been obvious to professiona
ls in the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Non-Patentability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Europe, the EPC and national laws, like CPI, outline specific categories
 of inventions that are not eligible for patent protection.
 This non-patentability stems from various reasons, including the nature
 of the invention, moral considerations, and the aim to protect public interests.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Non-Inventions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Aesthetic creations: items that are purely artistic or aesthetic in nature
 are not considered inventions under patent law because they do not possess
 a technical character or industrial application.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mental acts: ideas, business methods, and social practices are not patentable
 as they do not translate into a technical solution to a technical problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Non-Patentable Fields (Non-Industrial)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Medical field (Articles L.
 611-16 / EPC: Article 53): methods for treatment by surgery or therapy
 and diagnostic methods practiced on the human or animal body are excluded
 from patentability to ensure that medical and veterinary professionals
 can freely use their skills and knowledge for the benefit of all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Biological field and human body (Articles L.
 611-18 and 19 / EPC: Article 53-R29): the human body at various stages
 of formation and development, and the simple discovery of one of its elements,
 including the sequence or partial sequence of a gene, cannot be patented.
 However, an application of a gene sequence for industrial purposes can
 be patented.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Specific Exclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Computer programs (Article L.
 611-10 / EPC: Article 52): software or computer programs are not patentable
 to the extent that the patent application relates to the software alone,
 rather than a technical process or method involving the software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Biological matter: certain biological processes and uses of biological material
 are excluded from patentability, such as cloning human beings, modifying
 the germ line genetic identity of humans, and using human embryos for indutrial
 purposes.
 Processes that cause suffering to animals without substantial medical benefit
 are also excluded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Software inventions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Variations by country: while the US initially had few restrictions on patenting
 software inventions, Europe maintaints a more stringent approach, focusing
 on the technical contribution of the software.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Patentability criteria: in Europe, software can be part of a patentable
 invention if it serves a technical purpose or solves a technical problem,
 especially in the context of electronic data processing methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Authoring right: the creation of software code is protected under copyright
 law as an authoring right, emphasizing the distinction between copyright
 and patent protection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rights Conferred by the Patent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The grant of a patent confers specific rights to the patent holder, balancing
 the inventor's interests with public welfare.
 These rights delineate who can exploit the invention and under what conditions,
 encouraging innovation while ensuring that technological advancements benefit
 society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Property of Who?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Moral right
\series default
: remains with the inventor, recognizing their contribution and ensuring
 they are credited for their invention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Patrimonial rights
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Initially belong to the inventor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the context of employment, rights may be assigned to the employer if
 the invention is made in the course of the employee's duties and if there's
 a specific agreement regarding the assignment of rights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For independent contractors or unspecified contracts, rights typically remain
 with the inventor unless an agreement states otherwise.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Rights of the Patentee
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Patents provide a 
\series bold
right to forbid
\series default
 others from making, using, selling, or distributing the patented invention
 without permission.
 This right is territorial, applying only within the countries where the
 patent is granted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Why grant exclusivity?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Incentive for innovation: the exclusivity serves as an incentive for inventors
 to invest time and resources into developing new inventions by offering
 the possibility of financial return upon disclosure of the invention to
 the public (usually after 18 months from filing).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Limited right: the exclusivity is subject to specific criteria for patentability
, exceptions to patent rights, and a limited lifetime (typically 20 years),
 after which the invention enters the public domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Disputed right: the exclusivity can conflict with principles of commercial
 freedom and the ethos of open-source software, reflecting ongoing debates
 about the balance between private rights and public access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Limits of protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Product limits: a patented product can only be protected from unauthorized
 use, manufacture, or sale once; after it's sold, the patentee's control
 over that specific item ends (exhaustion of rights).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Monopoly limits:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Private use and experimentation on the patented product for non-commercial
 purposes are generally exempt from patent infringement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compulsory licenses may be granted by the state in cases of public interes,
 such as addressing shortages, reducing high prices, or promoting competition.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Obtaining the Property
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obtaining patent protection is a structured process that involves several
 key steps, each critical to securing and defining the legal protections
 afforded by a patent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Applying for a patent
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Preparation and filing: preparation of a comprehensive patent application
 that includes a detailed description of the invention, claims that define
 the scope of protection sought, and any relevant drawings or annexes.
 This application is then filed with the patent office in the country or
 countries where protection is desired.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Sustaining examination
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Requesting examination: after filing, the application undergoes an examination
 process where the patent office assesses whether the invention meets the
 criteria for patentability, including novelty, inventive step, and industrial
 applicability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Responding to office actions: the applicant may need to respond to queries
 or objections from the patent office, known as office actions, which might
 require amending the applicaiton to clarify the invention's novelty or
 inventive step.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Maintaining the patent
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Annuities payments: once granted, the patent holder must pay periodic fees,
 known as annuities, to maintain the patent's validity for its full term,
 typicaly up to 20 years.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Defining the Protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The protection a patent offers is defined through the application and examinatio
n process, particularly in the drafting of claims and the detailed description
 of the invention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Structure of a patent document
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Background
\series default
: sets the context by discussing state of the art and the technical field
 to which the invention belongs, highlighting existing problems or limitations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Summary
\series default
: provides a generic exposition of the invention, outlining its objectives
 and the technical solutions proposed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Detailed description
\series default
: describes in detail the preferred embodiments of the invention, often
 supported by drawings or diagrams, to enable a person skilled in the art
 to replicate the invention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Claims
\series default
: the most critical part of the patent document, defining the scope of protectio
n sought by delineating the novel aspects of the invention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Drawings and annexes
\series default
: visual representations of the invention and any additional material like
 DNA sequences or program code that supports the detailed description.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multi-National Granting Processes: Timelines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we want to file a patent in multiple countries, there are several considerati
ons to take into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For instance, let's say we file a patent in France.
 From the day of the filing, we have a period of one year until the 
\series bold
priority date 
\series default
is reached.
 Until the priority date, we can file the patent in other countries, or
 multi-national patent forms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After 18 months of the filing, the application is published.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After this, the examination periods in Europe and other countries can begin,
 as well as the preliminary examination for international applications under
 PTC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After 24 months, the patent can be granted in France.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After 30 months, the patent can be granted in other countries, as well as
 in selected EU countries under European applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, the national phases of the internation application can begin, including
 national examination and later granting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During all this time, the annuities must be paid for each different application
 process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Costs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Preparing and filing
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Attorney fees: these can be significant, as they cover the professional
 services of drafting and preparing the patent application.
 This typically includes a patentability search, drafting the specification
 and claims, and preparing drawings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Filing fees: paid to the patent office at the time of filing the application.
 These fees vary depending on the country and the size of the applicant
 entity.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Extending abroad
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
National phase entry fees: costs associated with entering the national phase
 of each country where protection is sought after an international PCT applicati
on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Translation costs: if extending protection to countries with different languages
, translations of the patent application will be required, which can be
 a significant expense.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Deadlines
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
12 months: the cost of filing a patent applicaiton in other countries or
 regions, claiming priority from the first application, within one year
 of the initial filing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
30 months: additional costs incurred for entering the regional phase of
 PCT applications.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Examination
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Examination fees: charged by the patent office to conduct a substantive
 examination of the patent application to determine if it meets the patentabilit
y criteria.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Response to office actions: additional attorney fees may be incurred to
 respond to objections or requests made by the patent office during examination.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Granting
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Grant fees: once a patent is allowed, some jurisdictions require a fee to
 finalize the grant of the patent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
EP national validation: in Europe, after grant by the Europan Patent Office,
 additional fees are required to validate the patent in each member state
 where protection is sought.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Maintaining or renewal
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Annual renewal fees: annuities paid to keep the patent in force after it
 has been granted, typically on an annual basis.
 They usually increase over the life of the patent.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Enforcing the Property Rights of Patents
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Patent rights provide the patent holder with legal means to enforce their
 exclusive rights to an invention.
 Enforcing these rights often involves monitoring the market, identifying
 potential ingringement, and takinf appropriate legal actions to stop unauthoriz
ed use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Managing the Property Right - Proprietor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Defense
\series default
: the patent owner must actively defend their patent, which includes several
 steps:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Detecting infringement: monitoring the market for products or processes
 that may infringe on the patented invention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Notifying: contacting the alleged infringer to notify them of the patent
 and the potential infringement, often through a cease and desists letter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Judicial action: if the infringement persists, the patent owner can initiate
 legal processings to enforce their rights.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Infringement action: legal proceedings can be initiated to seek remedies
 such as injunctions to stop the infringement, monetary damages, and sometimes
 the destruction of infringing goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Defending the patent: suring legal proceedings, the patent owner must be
 prepared to defend the validity of their patent, as it may be challenged
 by the alleged infringer.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Country dependent: enforcement mechanisms and legal procedures vary by country,
 requiring an understanding of local patent laws and judicial processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stakes/risks: the benefits of enforcing a patent include protecting market
 share and revenue streams, while the risks include the potential for the
 patent to be invalidated during legal proceedings.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Managing the Property Right - Challenger
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Information problem - cost: parties interested in entering a market with
 a new product or process must perform due diligence to ensure that they
 are not infringing on existing patens, which often involves significant
 costs related to patent searches and legal advice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Manufacturing/importing: companies need to be cautious when manufacturing
 or importing goods that may be covered by patents to avoid infringement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
OEM: original equipment manufacturers must endure that the products they
 manufacture for other companies do not infringe on patents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Subcontractors: companies using subcontractors must ensure that any products
 or processes used do not infringe on patents, which may require contracts
 with indemnity clauses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Retailers: retailers selling products must also be wary of patent infringement
 issues, which could lead to legal action against them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Contract/warranties: agreements involving the manufacture, supply, or sale
 of products should include warranties against patent infringement to protect
 against liability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Stakes/risks: the risks for a challenger include potential legal action
 for patent infringement and associated costs, while the stakes involve
 being able to oeprate in the market and offer new products or services.
\end_layout

